data.title: Probobly the biggest power move of my life

images.description: My landlord wanted to raise my rent from $1500 a month to $2000 a month for a 970 square foot apartment. My fiance and I moved here last year and rent prices in our area have since gotten worse. We tried to negotiate a better lease because we loved this apartment and did not want to move, but the landlord refused to budge. Thanks to my fiance's father being a rockstar realtor, we were able to get a good deal on a house just 5 minutes away. The house is about 1200 square feet and will cost about the same per month as our old lease agreement. So yea, fuck landlords.

data.title: I think adapting cities and infrastructure to change is a monumental challenge, especially for the usually inept institutions of government in charge of it.

images.description:
I think adapting cities and infrastructure to change is a monumental challenge, especially for the usually inept institutions of government in charge of it.
Personally one thing I think not often considered is the less autonomy we have, the more cities represent a utilitarian human farm. People have to go to office sectors from their residential sectors and shop at retail sectors. Which is great for maximum utilization and economic efficiency, which is necessary for less autonomous people, but not so great for a harmonious city. Solve for one, alleviate the other.
